{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611356"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:09:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:09:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16209"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16209"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.32,0.32,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8900"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115379"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8900"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16209"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97382"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"8403"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21181"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115379"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe breast contains specialised stromal tissues that provide structural support and regulate development. The two main types are interlobular and intralobular stroma.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the composition and characteristics of interlobular stroma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Consists of loose connective tissue around milk ducts","Contains mainly adipose tissue and fibroblasts","Comprises dense collagen and elastic fibres","Shows monthly changes with menstrual cycle","Contains predominantly lymphoid tissue"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edense collagen and elastic fibres\u003C/strong\u003E are the main components of interlobular stroma, which provides the structural framework of the breast. This tissue is not hormone-responsive and maintains its composition throughout the menstrual cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConsists of loose connective tissue around milk ducts\u003C/strong\u003E describes intralobular stroma, which is more specialised and hormone-responsive. \u003Cstrong\u003EContains mainly adipose tissue and fibroblasts\u003C/strong\u003E is partially accurate as these components are present, but the main constituent is dense collagenous tissue. \u003Cstrong\u003EShows monthly changes with menstrual cycle\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of intralobular stroma rather than interlobular stroma, which is not hormone-responsive. \u003Cstrong\u003EContains predominantly lymphoid tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as while some immune cells may be present, the main component is dense connective tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe interlobular stroma maintains breast shape and provides attachment points for Cooper\u0027s ligaments. It differs from the more specialised intralobular stroma that immediately surrounds the glandular tissue and responds to hormonal changes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The interlobular stroma forms the majority of breast tissue and consists of dense collagenous and elastic tissue.","Intralobular stroma is the hormone-responsive tissue that immediately surrounds the terminal duct lobular units (TDLUs).","The different types of breast stroma have distinct compositions and functions in supporting breast architecture."],"references":["Wiseman BS, Werb Z. Stromal effects on mammary gland development and breast cancer. Science. 2002 May 10;296(5570):1046-9. doi: 10.1126/science.1067431. PMID: 12004111; PMCID: PMC2788989.","Shekhar MP, Werdell J, Santner SJ, Pauley RJ, Tait L. Breast stroma plays a dominant regulatory role in breast epithelial growth and differentiation: implications for tumor development and progression. Cancer Res. 2001 Feb 15;61(4):1320-6. PMID: 11245428.","Arendt LM, Rudnick JA, Keller PJ, Kuperwasser C. Stroma in breast development and disease. Semin Cell Dev Biol. 2010 Feb;21(1):11-8. doi: 10.1016/j.semcdb.2009.10.003. Epub 2009 Oct 24. PMID: 19857593; PMCID: PMC2823823.","Javed A, Lteif A. Development of the human breast. Semin Plast Surg. 2013 Feb;27(1):5-12. doi: 10.1055/s-0033-1343989. PMID: 24872732; PMCID: PMC3706056.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97382"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16209"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97382"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T14:13:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T14:15:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8900"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115379"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms"